author: @AshieduJude
text: What we refuse to accept is the reality, that Data science, analysis and engineering were not meant to be standalone roles in most organisations. You are to use Data related jobs as complementary skillsets like Excel, Word, PowerPoint and other programs to your other main job description.  You can be a medical professional and data analyst with medical data. As an Educator, data science, analysis etc complement student data processing and visualization.  HR personnel needs the Data science/analysis skillset as a complement to the organisational toolkit, not stand alone.  Else you will find yourself in and out of your primary job functions as a Data analyst.

author: @dmm.2680
text: Thank you so very very much for this video. I happened to be a veteran with an opportunity to purse a credential in Data Analysis and really would not have had any clue to these critically important points you raise.  This is a highly valuable video and I am so glad you chose the title you did because if you search the internet and Youtube courses and certificates in Data Analysis is all the rage.  One point that did occur to me was that also all these people with entry level training in Data Analytics are hitting the market, and will overpopulate the workforce causing there to be too many entry level DA techs and few with the mid-level and senior experience needed. I already had the same thing happen with training in Litigation Technology eDiscovery. I took a certificate course and because of the need for a certain amount of experience to start 3-5 years I was never able to get a job in the field.  So again, excellent points made in this video that novices in the DA and technology field would otherwise have no knowledge or understanding about.  You have helped me to make a clear decision that a professional pursuit of a career in the Data Analytics field is out.  This does not mean however that I will not watch a few videos and take a course of two so that I am knowledgeable about the field in general.  Thank you again Alex!!

author: @abbddos
text: I've been a data analyst for several UN agencies for about 12 years now.  If you love technology and contributing to some innovation,  data analysis is not your thing.    You'll be doing the same thing over and over again every day,  every week and every month.  You might try something new with Python and automation,  but soon, it will too become same old boring routine.    The hard part is not that the data we deal with is large or complex.  On contrary,  it is very simple. The difficulty comes when you'd like to try a new idea or technology on something terribly simple. For God's sakes,  I had cases where using Excel was an overkill.   The worst part I face in my job is explaining what I did to others I work with.  I admit that I'm not very socially skilled, but having to explain the very basics over and over again to staff members who are supposed to be seniors is really tedious.

author: @Jenkkimie
text: Been doing a school project for data-analytics and AI. Took data thinking It was a good set at first glance but then it became clear there had a lot of dirty and bad data that needed a lot of cleaning,  some problems were quite complex like having a row that contained several different kind of marking standards and then trying to extract a normalized year string from that column. Then became the unforeseen values which took a lot of research of the data and then finding out what they should be. Should they be filled with forward fill propagation or left alone? Fake data or risk keeping it the way it was?  Not easy answers, not for someone new like me. Although I have enjoyed it. It is complex, difficult, often you get stuck and it takes a lot of additional research but it is all the same rewarding when you finally get a step closer to what you want the data to look like for whatever use purposes you need it for. Some challenges are about data-analytics and some are understanding the data itself. Iteration and patience are keys in data-analytics in my opinion.

author: @nunyabiznez6381
text: So I just got an ad from Google for that data analytics certification.  After spending hours I could not find a single advertisement for a job for a data analyst anywhere in my state (population over 20 million).   I found three advertisements for a data analyst in the U.S. and the one that had the lowest qualification requirements requires certification in data analytics, a bachelor's degree and five years experience in the field and pays $39,000 to start.   Google claims that there are over 300,000 jobs available in the U.S. for a data analyst and that the average entry level pay is $67k+ and that all you need is the certificate to get the job.   What am I missing?   Oh and I'm not that worried about getting rich.  I just want a job that pays more than kitchen manager at McDonald's which was my last job.   Honestly, $30k and a decent healthcare plan would do it for me as I don't have many more years until I'm collecting social security.

author: @nunyabiznez6381
text: There are many kinds of doctors that don't need to see a lot of blood.  Mostly just avoid being an E.R. doctor or a surgeon.   Most oncologists don't see a lot of blood other than via needles and those are mostly handled by nurses.  Radiation oncology specialists don't work with blood at all.  Anesthesiologists don't work directly with blood.  Psychiatrists don't usually work with blood except the occasional patient that likes to cut themselves.  There are others but these are a few good examples and some make an incredible amount of money.

author: @adamhuman6201
text: 5 Reasons, what I take from the video.  1. Don't do it if you are not a self learner. 2. Not for people who become frustrated easily. Because you run into a lot of roadblocks. Need to have high tolerance for frustration. 3. You have to do ton of manual work, such as moving stuff from different applications. 4. Don't do it if you cannot work with people. Communication is imperative. 5. This is not a quick become rich scheme. Need at least about 5-10 years of experience to make a good buck. You grow as you keep learning.  Thank you Alex.

author: @mikereeves282
text: I am in an analytics role for a large Corp. I often get tasked with creating analysis on financial data that the financial analysts do not have the technical capability to execute. I primarily use 3 technology components to do this: 1. Writing code to extract data from the source  2. Use of an analytical modeling tool such as SPSS modeler or Alteryx 3. Visualization of the results in cognos   Number 2 in the list above is where all of the ‚Äúmagic‚Äù happens. I feel It allows me to appear much smarter than I actually am. Access and the use of tools like that are key to separating yourself from the many people that have advanced excel skills, which is a large number of people. Hope this helps!
